# Step1: Read the column description and ensure you understand each attribute well.

# Attribute Information: 
# Details of attribues in data set are described below:

# 1. ID -> Customer ID
# 2. Age -> Customer's age in completed years
# 3. Experience -> Number of years of professional experience
# 4. Income -> Annual income of the customer ($000)
# 5. ZIP Code -> Home Address ZIP code
# 6. Family -> Family size of the customer
# 7. CCAvg -> Average spending on credit cards per month ($000)
# 8. Education -> Education Level (1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate; 3: Advanced/Professional)
# 9. Mortgage -> Value of house mortgage if any. ($000)
# 10. Personal Loan -> Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign?
# 11. Securities Account -> Does the customer have a securities account with the bank?
# 12. CD Account -> Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank? 
# 13. Online -> Does the customer use internet banking facilities? 
# 14. Credit card : Does the customer use a credit card issued by UniversalBank?

In [14]:
def missing_check(df):
    total = df.isnull().sum().sort_values(ascending=False)   # total number of null values
    percent = (df.isnull().sum()/df.isnull().count()).sort_values(ascending=False)  # percentage of values that are null
    missing_data = pd.concat([total, percent], axis=1, keys=['Total', 'Percent'])  # putting the above two together
    return missing_data # return the dataframe
missing_check(dataframe)

def SVM_classifier(x_train,x_test,y_train,y_test):
  model=svm.SVC()
  model.fit(x_train,y_train)
  y_pred = model.predict(x_test)
  print(classification_report(y_test,y_pred))
  print(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred))
  print('F1-Score:', f1_score(y_test, y_pred, average='weighted'))

def KNN_classifier(x_train,x_test,y_train,y_test):
  model= KNeighborsClassifier()

def NB_classifier(x_train,x_test,y_train,y_test):

# Step 7: Give your reasoning on which is the best model in this case and why it performs better?
In [105]:
#Solution: As the data set is biased (since the number of entries of people not having taken personal loan is far
#greater than the number of people who have taken personal loan) the model which has the best F1 score is supposed to be 
#the best model.

# Since the value for SVM is the highest () it is supposed to be to best model for this data set. However, since the question 
# mentions only three models: Logistic regression, KNN and Naive Bayes, the best modelout of the three is KNN with a high score
# I think KNN works best for this data set due to the high value of co-relation between certain data attributes. 
# KNN uses the technique of trying to find similarities between data points.
# We have not used any hyper parameter optimization so that we could comapre the models/algortithms in a same way and the 
#training cost of all the models seems to be equal.
#Therefore it seems to perform best on this data.
